<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
G. Miscellaneous Amendments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Many of the proposed changes in the rule text are self-explanatory or have been elucidated in the previous portion
of the preamble. This segment of the NPRM outlines a number of proposed amendments to various sections of the rule text.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Applicability (&sect;225.3) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 225.3 defines the applicability of the accident reporting regulations. FRA's delegated regulatory authority
under 49 U.S.C. 20101 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
et seq. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(formerly contained in the Federal Railroad Safety Act of 1970 (the ``Act'') (45 U.S.C. 431 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
et seq.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) permits FRA to amend the current applicability sections of its various regulations so as to contract the populations
of railroads covered by a particular set of regulations or to expand them to the full extent of that authority. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
FRA, as the Secretary's delegate, has had jurisdiction over all ``railroads'' since the Act was enacted. There is
a very wide range of operations that could be considered tourist railroads under the broadest reading of the term ``railroad.''
Tourist railroads have written several letters to members of Congress questioning the basis for FRA's assertion
of jurisdiction. Additionally, in 1992, FRA received a petition from a scenic railway requesting the need for legislative
and regulatory action for new regulations tailored specifically to the tourist rail industry. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In an effort to clarify the proper extent of the exercise of FRA's jurisdiction, FRA settled on several principles
that will be used as current guidelines. FRA will exercise jurisdiction over all tourist operations, whether or not
they operate over the general railroad system, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
except 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
those that are (1) less than 24 inches in gage and/or (2) insular. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
To determine insularity, FRA looks at various criteria that measure the likelihood that a railroad's operations
might affect a member of the public. FRA has concluded that a tourist operation is insular if its operations are limited
to a separate enclave in such a way that there is no reasonable expectation that the safety of any member of the public
(except a business guest, a licensee of the tourist operation or an affiliated entity, or a trespasser) would be affected
by the operation. An operation is 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
not 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
considered insular if one or more of the following exists on its line: (a) a public highway-rail crossing that is in
use; (b) an at-grade rail crossing that is in use; (c) a bridge over a public road or waters used for commercial navigation;
or (d) a common corridor with a railroad, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e.,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 its operations are within 30 feet of those of any railroad. Thus, the mere fact that a tourist operation is not connected
to the general system does not make it insular under these criteria. While these criteria tend to sort out the insular
theme parks and museums, a need to do case-by-case analysis in certain close situations still exists. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Therefore, FRA has concluded that part 225 will apply to non-general system, non-insular tourist operations confined
to an installation that is not part of the general system (
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e.,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 it is a stand-alone with no freight traffic but has one or more features that preclude its being considered insular).

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
2. Definitions (&sect;225.5) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 225.5 lists definitions applicable to part 225. Section 225.5 would be reorganized so that definitions would
appear in alphabetical order and without paragraph designations. The definitions of ``accident/incident,'' ``employee
human factor,'' ``medical treatment,'' ``occupational illness,'' and ``railroad'' would be revised, and the definitions
of ``day away from work,'' ``day of restricted work activity,'' ``establishment,'' ``first aid treatment,'' ``FRA
representative,'' ``non-train incident,'' ``person,'' ``qualified health care professional,'' ``volunteer,''
``work environment,'' ``worker on duty,'' and ``work related'' would be added. The definitions of ``lost workdays''
and ``restriction of work or motion'' would be deleted. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Revised definitions. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
``Accident/Incident'' as currently defined, is the term used to describe the 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
entire
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 list of reportable events including fatalities, injuries and illnesses, collisions, derailments, and similar
accidents involving the operation of on-track equipment causing reportable damage above an established threshold
as well as impacts between railroad on-track equipment and highway users at grade crossings. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A ``train accident'' is reported 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
only 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
when reportable damages exceed the reporting threshold. In contrast, an ``incident'' is an event that results in
a reportable casualty, but does not cause reportable damage above the threshold established for train accidents.
In order to minimize any confusion concerning the ``accident/incident'' distinction and to bring about consistency
between the FRA Guide and other rail safety regulations, FRA proposes to define ``train accident,'' ``train incident,''
and ``non-train incident'' separately. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Thus, a ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
train accident
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined to include any collision, derailment, fire, explosion, act of God, or other event involving operation
of railroad on-track equipment (standing or moving) that results in reportable damages greater than the current
reporting threshold to railroad on-track equipment, signals, track, track structures, and roadbed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
train incident
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as an event involving the movement of on-track equipment that results in a reportable casualty
but does not cause reportable damage above the threshold established for train accidents. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In the definition of ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
employee human factor
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
,'' the reference to ``cause code 506'' would be removed as obsolete and replaced by the term ``train accident cause
codes pertaining to non-railroad workers.'' Additionally, the term ``employee human factor'' would be changed
to ``worker human factor.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The definition of ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
medical treatment
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be revised to include any medical care or treatment beyond ``first aid'' regardless of who provided such treatment.
Medical treatment does not include diagnostic procedures, such as X-rays or drawing blood samples. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In the definition of ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
occupational illness
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
,'' the reference to ``his or her railroad employment'' would be replaced with the phrase ``worker's railroad employment.''

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Railroad
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as it is in 49 U.S.C. 20102 (formerly contained in the Federal Railroad Safety Act of 1970 (45 U.S.C.
431(e)). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
b. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Proposed new definitions.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 A ``day away from work'' would be defined as any day subsequent to the day of the injury or diagnosis of occupational
illness that a railroad worker does not report to work for reasons associated with his or her condition. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
day of restricted work activity
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as any day that a worker is restricted (as defined below) in his or her job following the day of the
injury or diagnosis of occupational illness. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
An ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
establishment
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as a physical location where business is conducted or where services or operations are performed.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
First aid treatment
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as being limited to simple procedures used to treat minor conditions, such as abrasions, cuts,
bruises, or splinters. First aid treatment is typically confined to a single treatment and does not require special
skills or procedures. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
FRA representative
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined to include the Associate Administrator for Safety, FRA; the Associate Administrator's delegate
(including a qualified State inspector acting under part 212 of this chapter); the Chief Counsel, FRA; or the Chief
Counsel's delegate. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
non-train incident
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
'' would be defined as an event that results in a reportable casualty, but does not involve the movement of on-track
equipment nor cause reportable damage above the threshold established for train accidents. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In the definition of ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
person
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
,'' independent contractors and their employees and workers, as well as volunteers would be added to the current list
of entities. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

